RIBCAGE

ribcage is the enclosure bone for the torso — the protective lattice around heart, lungs, and the chemistry engine
where the skull encloses the upper region's high-coherence citizens, ribcage encloses the body's rhythm-generating organs, the citizens that drive the heartbeat that paces every other floor of the city
ribcage is built of paired ribs hinged on the spine; it expands and contracts with respiration so the enclosed citizens have room to breathe and beat

observe 0_quseptit.rana
observe spine.xb
observe skull.xb
observe pelvis.xb
observe 2_chemical.rana

the 7 properties of ribcage at rest:
1 ENERGY low-medium: persistent rhythmic motion as the cage expands and contracts
2 PHASE locked to the cardiac and respiratory rhythms
3 SPIN low oscillation: the cage flexes but does not rotate
4 CHARGE neutral
5 COHERENCE high: a discontinuous ribcage compromises the rhythm of what it encloses
6 COUPLING strong with spine (rib hinges) and with heart/chemistry citizens within
7 OBSERVER zero: ribcage does not watch; it holds

THE ENCLOSED REGION

ribcage encloses the torso between roughly Y00 (the diaphragm boundary) and Y08 (the upper-thoracic boundary at skull base)
this includes the heart citizen, the chemistry engine, the hippocampus's lower extensions, and the descending vagal nerve traffic from skull
the heart's pulse rhythm originates here and propagates through spine to every other floor

THE PAIRED RIBS

ribcage is twelve paired ribs, hinged on the spine
the upper seven pairs are true ribs, attached anteriorly to the sternum
the next three pairs are false ribs, attached to the rib above
the lowest two pairs are floating ribs, attached only at the spine

each rib is a flexible arc that allows the cage to expand outward during inspiration and recoil inward during expiration
this expansion drives respiratory rhythm — the secondary clock to the cardiac primary

THE STERNUM

at the front midline, the ribcage closes on the sternum
the sternum is the anterior anchor where true ribs converge
the sternum's center is the body's most-protected location for the heart citizen

THE DIAPHRAGM BOUNDARY

at Y00, the diaphragm separates ribcage from the abdominal region
this is not a bone but a tendinous wall; ribcage's lower edge meets it
respiratory rhythm originates at this boundary

VERB enclose
hold the rhythm-generating citizens inside a flexible boundary
the cage is rigid enough to protect, supple enough to move with the rhythm

VERB respire
expand and contract on the respiratory cycle
this expansion does mechanical work on the lungs (when present in the architecture), not just protection
inspiration is active; expiration is passive recoil

VERB transmit_pulse
let the cardiac heartbeat propagate through the cage walls outward
the cardiac pulse is felt at the chest wall as well as at the wrist; ribcage is the cardiac signal's first transmission medium

VERB protect
when external impact arrives at the torso, absorb through the rib lattice and dissipate via spine
the heart and chemistry citizens experience only damped versions of external blows

VERB hinge_at_spine
each rib pair joins the spine via two facet joints
these joints permit the small rotational movement needed for breathing
they do not permit large displacement; the cage is shape-stable

a ribcage is not a wall
a ribcage is a breathing lattice
unlike skull which is rigid coherence-preservation, ribcage is rhythmic flexible-protection
the torso's citizens need both safety and motion; ribcage provides both at once
